The leaders of the two Koreas shook hands at the Military Demarcation Line at 9:30 am on Friday. This meeting, the first in 11 years, holds the attention of not only the two countries involved, but also the international community.   

Photo taken on April 27, 2018 at the media center in Goyang, South Korea, shows a screen broadcasting South Korean President Moon Jae-in (R) shaking hands with top leader of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Kim Jong Un in the border village of Panmunjom. Moon Jae-in arrived Friday morning in the border village of Panmunjom for his first summit with Kim Jong Un. (Xinhua/Wang Jingqiang)A live broadcast of the meeting started to stream on online platforms and televisions with South Korean President Moon Jae-in's car group heading to Panmunjom, where he would meet with North Korean leader Kim Jong-un.Global Times reporters watched the live broadcast of the Friday meeting in the Korea International Exhibition Center in Goyang, South Korea.The press center burst into a round of applause when Kim and Moon shook hands and chatted while standing on their respective sides of the border, which is marked by a raised, foot-wide concrete line.Kim then invited Moon to cross the inter-Korean border to the North Korean side. Moon briefly crossed the border with Kim before they returned to the South Korean side.An announcement over the speaker in the press center said that "this is the moment, the world is waiting."After the morning session of the summit finishes, the two sides will have separate luncheons and time to rest. Reporters from South Korean media said to the Global Times on Friday that they were touched by the moment when the two leaders shook hands. "The Korean Peninsula has experienced a lingering shadow of war over the past several months, but all of a sudden, the situation gets better. [Peace] that we have never thought about may be realized soon," Sing Yeong-nan, a South Korean reporter, told the Global Times. Backgrounder: the AIIB explainedImpact of anti-corruption campaignBig changes in China's top military brass How China, Japan can cooperate on B&RChina fast-tracks nuclear energy industryChinese forest officials slam UK elephant charity report Border wall will do nothing to resolve immigration issuesSurge in Chinese learningHitting the streets How To Say Love To A Chinese Girl

